    <div class="statement-box">
      <h2>Calling for a Ceasefire and the Release of Hostages</h2>

      <p><strong>During the war in Vietnam, Thầy (Thich Nhat Hanh) called for a unilateral ceasefire</strong>—not as a political strategy, but as a deep act of compassion. Many said the war was necessary to stop communism, but Thầy reminded us not to be caught in ideology.</p>

      <p>Today, we hear similar justifications for violence. Yet we know that bombs and weapons do not defeat ideas. <strong>War and violence often strengthens ideologies. Violence, and our fear of it, cannot be overcome with more violence.</strong></p>

      <p>Millions of people are starving, bombs continue to fall. Cities are turned to rubble. Hostages are still being held. <strong>The suffering is unimaginable.</strong></p>

      <p><strong>Acknowledging that many of our governments are directly supporting or participating in violence, we cannot be silent.</strong></p>

      <p>The <strong>14 Mindfulness Trainings</strong>, born in the fire of war, call us as a community to act together, nurturing seeds of compassion and peace in this moment, transcending notions and views:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Ninth Training calls us</strong> to speak truthfully and lovingly against injustice—even when it threatens our safety. </li>
        <li><strong>The Tenth Training reminds us</strong> we must take a clear stand against oppression and injustice, while not using our community as a political instrument.</li>
        <li><strong>The Twelfth Training calls us to protect life.</strong> Not to kill, and not to let others kill. </li>
      </ul>

      <p><strong>We also affirm: to peacefully challenge Israeli and US state violence is love in action</strong>—not antisemitism, not hatred, not support for opposing violence or a particular political outcome.</p>

      <p>We affirm the right of all people to self-determination, safety, and justice.</p>

      <p><strong>We call on all practitioners in the Plum Village tradition—and all people moved by compassion—to raise again and again the call for an immediate ceasefire in Gaza and beyond and the release of all hostages.</strong></p>

      <p><strong>We call for immediate international action to protect human life, support humanitarian aid, and the use of diplomacy, sanctions, boycotts, nonviolent civil disobedience, and the withdrawal of all military support to end the violence.</strong></p>

      <p>We aspire to look at everyone with the eyes of compassion, even those presently causing harm. We commit to cultivating our own understanding, compassion, and peace through our collective and personal practice and through building community.</p>

      <p>We commend all actions of all people everywhere, all practitioners, both lay and monastic, working together, both quietly and publicly, toward compassion, justice, and peace.</p>
    </div>

