      <h2>Wisdom from Our Teacher</h2>
      <p>These teachings from Thầy guide our understanding of nonviolent response to conflict:</p>

      <details class="reference-item">
        <summary><strong>Letter from Thầy on War and Peace</strong></summary>
        <div class="reference-content">
          <p><em>From "In Love and Trust"</em></p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>Dear friends,</p>
            <p>I know that you are suffering, just as I am. War not only kills people; it also destroys the most beautiful and fragile elements in the human soul. I have seen children die from bombs, mothers weeping beside the bodies of their children. I have seen young soldiers — from both sides — with empty eyes, the eyes of those who have lost faith in humanity.</p>
            <p>I am not writing these lines to accuse anyone, but to share a truth: we cannot kill each other and expect peace.</p>
            <p>We need to sit down together, not as enemies, but as human beings who suffer, who long to live in safety and harmony.</p>
            <p>As a monk, I do not take sides in a war. I choose the side of peace. I choose to stand with all those who believe that love is stronger than hatred, that deep understanding can transform fear and anger.</p>
            <p>If you truly want to end war, you cannot only go out and protest in the streets. You must also turn inward to see the roots of violence within yourself: discrimination, indifference, and anger.</p>
            <p>We need a revolution —but not a revolution of violence. We need a revolution of consciousness, a revolution of mindfulness, a revolution of love.</p>
            <p>Each mindful breath, each peaceful step, each word spoken with understanding— is an act of peace.</p>
            <p>I believe you can do this. And I pray for you, just as I pray for all who are lost, who are suffering, and who are searching for the way home.</p>
            <p>Peace is not a dream. Peace is real — if you live each moment in peace.</p>
            <p>With love,<br>Thích Nhất Hạnh</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="reference-item">
        <summary><strong>A Proposal for Peace (Vietnam War)</strong></summary>
        <div class="reference-content">
          <p><em>From "Love in Action, Writings on Nonviolent Social Change"</em></p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>Since coming to the United States, I have been asked repeatedly to outline concrete proposals for ending the strife in Vietnam... My solution would be along the following lines:</p>
            <ol>
              <li>A cessation of the bombing, north and south.</li>
              <li>Limitation of all military operations by U.S. and South Vietnamese forces to defensive actions: in effect, a cease-fire if the Vietcong respond in kind.</li>
              <li>A convincing demonstration of the U.S. intention to withdraw its forces from Vietnam over a specified period of months, with withdrawal actually beginning to take place as a sign of sincerity.</li>
              <li>A clear statement by the U.S. of its desire to help the Vietnamese people to have a government truly responsive to Vietnamese aspirations...</li>
              <li>A generous effort to help rebuild, in light of the destruction that has been wreaked upon Vietnam...</li>
            </ol>
            <p>Finally, if some may question why I ask the U.S. to take the first step, it is because the U.S. is militarily the strongest nation in the world. No one can accuse it of cowardice if it chooses to seek peace. To be a genuine leader requires moral strength as well as big guns. America's history suggests that she has the potential to provide the world this leadership.</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>

      <details class="reference-item">
        <summary><strong>Understanding Both Sides</strong></summary>
        <div class="reference-content">
          <p><em>From "Being Peace"</em></p>
          <blockquote>
            <p>During the war in Vietnam, we young Buddhists organized ourselves to help victims of the war rebuild villages that had been destroyed by the bombs. Many of us died during service, not only because of the bombs and the bullets, but because of the people who suspected us of being on the other side. We were able to understand the suffering of both sides, the communists and the anti-communists. We tried to be open to both, to understand this side and to understand that side, to be one with them. That is why we did not take a side, even though the whole world took sides.</p>
            <p>We tried to tell people our perception of the situation: that we wanted to stop the fighting. But the bombs were so loud. Sometimes we had to burn ourselves alive to get the message across, but even then the world couldn't hear us. They thought it was a political action. They didn't know that it was a purely human action to be heard, to be understood. We didn't want a victory, we wanted reconciliation.</p>
            <p>The situation of the world is still like this. People identify completely with one side, one ideology. To understand the suffering and the fear of a citizen of another country, we have to become one with him. To do so is dangerous—we will be suspected by both sides. But if we don't do it, if we align ourselves with one side or the other, we will lose our chance to work for peace. Reconciliation is to understand both sides, to go to one side and describe the suffering being endured by the other side, and then to go to the other side and describe the suffering being endured by the first side. Doing only that will be a great help for peace.</p>
          </blockquote>
        </div>
      </details>
